00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:29.550
SPEAKER: Oh, wow.

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:32.100
And you wrote "Once On
This Island," I think,

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:33.720
something like 27 years ago.

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:34.770
LYNN AHRENS: Yeah.

00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:36.353
SPEAKER: How did
this show come about?

00:06:36.353 --> 00:06:37.650
What's the origin story?

00:06:37.650 --> 00:06:40.350
LYNN AHRENS: Well, when
you do musical theater,

00:06:40.350 --> 00:06:42.250
you never can count
on the results.

00:06:42.250 --> 00:06:44.490
And so our first show
had gone to Off-Broadway,

00:06:44.490 --> 00:06:48.960
a show called "Lucky Stiff"
about a shoe salesman

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:52.351
who takes a dead body on
vacation in a wheelchair.

00:06:52.351 --> 00:06:52.850
It was--

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:53.790
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: It
was very dramatic.

00:06:53.790 --> 00:06:55.700
LYNN AHRENS: --before
"Weekend at Bernie's."

00:06:55.700 --> 00:06:56.494
It was before that.

00:06:56.494 --> 00:06:57.910
And you know, it
was Off-Broadway.

00:06:57.910 --> 00:06:59.310
It had a limited run.

00:06:59.310 --> 00:07:03.000
And we were sort of desperate
to start a next project.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.790
And I went to a
bookstore where they--

00:07:05.790 --> 00:07:07.980
remember bookstores?

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:12.270
And they had a used
book shelf, area.

00:07:12.270 --> 00:07:15.270
And I pulled a little novel off
the shelf, and I looked at it,

00:07:15.270 --> 00:07:18.570
and it had a very colorful
title and colorful cover.

00:07:18.570 --> 00:07:21.720
And I opened it up, and
the first words were,

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:24.360
"There is an island
where rivers run deep,

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:26.040
where the sea
sparkling in the sun

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:27.780
earns it the name
Jewel of the Antilles."

00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:29.446
The first words on
the page, and I went,

00:07:29.446 --> 00:07:31.017
[GASPS] this is a musical.

00:07:31.017 --> 00:07:32.850
And I slammed the book
shut, and I ran home.

00:07:32.850 --> 00:07:34.560
I bought it for $1.50.

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:35.850
I didn't even haggle.

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:40.020
And I took it home, read it,
and took a cab right over

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:40.590
to Stephen's.

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:42.340
And I said, I think I
found the next show.

00:07:42.340 --> 00:07:43.770
So that's how that
happened, yeah.

00:07:43.770 --> 00:07:45.353
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: I
was just listening

00:07:45.353 --> 00:07:47.790
to a lot of world music at
the time, just for pleasure.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:50.650
Paul Simon had come out
with his seminal record

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:53.670
"Graceland," which
was his voice but it's

00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:56.520
filtered through the South
African music of Ladysmith

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:57.372
Black Mambazo.

00:07:57.372 --> 00:07:59.830
And I was listening to all that
kind of stuff just for fun.

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:03.360
And I just thought, this
could be a really cool basis

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:04.890
for a theater score
that could have

00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:06.570
world music elements in it.

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:10.170
And they never said which
island it was in the book.

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:12.270
So I borrowed a
little from here,

00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:15.570
a little from there,
some South American

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:17.440
music, some American gospel.

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:20.220
And I just made it my own.

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:23.050
And it was a fantastic
project to work on.

00:08:23.050 --> 00:08:25.140
It was the fastest
writing we had ever done.

00:08:25.140 --> 00:08:26.820
We wrote pretty
much the first draft

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:28.570
of the show in six months.

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:29.680
SPEAKER: Oh, wow.

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:32.628
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
And that's fast.

00:08:32.628 --> 00:08:34.919
SPEAKER: What is your process
like in the room together

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:35.789
as collaborators?

00:08:35.789 --> 00:08:37.890
Like, do you have
different styles?

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:39.460
How does that work together?

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:41.370
LYNN AHRENS: Well, over
the years, you know,

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:43.350
collaboration-- you're
all collaborators

00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:44.320
in one form or another.

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:48.150
And what we've found in all
of these 30-something years

00:08:48.150 --> 00:08:51.270
that we've been working together
is that it keeps changing.

00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:54.810
So back then, we would sit in
the room every day at a piano,

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:56.732
we would work for
a couple hours,

00:08:56.732 --> 00:08:59.190
then we would have Chinese
food, then we would have coffee,

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:00.385
then we would get
over-caffeinated--

00:09:00.385 --> 00:09:02.370
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: And Lynn would
say, don't eat the egg roll,

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:04.060
because I would
immediately fall asleep.

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:04.779
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:04.779 --> 00:09:07.320
LYNN AHRENS: You know, I got to
know, don't eat the egg roll.

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:09.420
And by the end of the
day, all the tempos

00:09:09.420 --> 00:09:12.580
were too fast, because we were
so hyper from a lot of coffee.

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:14.010
And that was then.

00:09:14.010 --> 00:09:17.630
And then we gradually, you know,
switched to decaf and salads.

00:09:17.630 --> 00:09:18.345
And--

00:09:18.345 --> 00:09:21.140
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:25.100
But the actual working process,
sometimes it's lyrics first.

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:26.260
Sometimes it's music first.

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:28.260
A lot of the time, it's
sort of like a ping pong

00:09:28.260 --> 00:09:31.410
match, where he'll go,
do do do do do do do do,

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:32.910
you know, and I'll
say some words.

00:09:32.910 --> 00:09:35.730
And I'll get the computer, and
we'll start working together.

00:09:35.730 --> 00:09:37.650
And sometimes he'll
email me a tune.

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:39.660
And sometimes I'll
email him lyrics.

00:09:39.660 --> 00:09:41.280
In the old days, it was faxing.

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:44.100
Or I would do dramatic readings
on his answering machine.

00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:45.180
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: Oh,
her dramatic readings

00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:45.910
were so great.

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:47.655
She would actually do them in
the voice of the character.

00:09:47.655 --> 00:09:48.420
LYNN AHRENS: Yes.

00:09:48.420 --> 00:09:50.660
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
And you know, this

00:09:50.660 --> 00:09:54.086
was before email,
and Google, before--

00:09:54.086 --> 00:09:54.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:55.590
LYNN AHRENS: It
was before the car.

00:09:55.590 --> 00:09:57.150
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: Yeah,
but these were so great.

00:09:57.150 --> 00:09:58.350
These tapes were great.

00:09:58.350 --> 00:09:59.183
They were wonderful.

00:09:59.183 --> 00:10:00.210
SPEAKER: Oh, wow.

00:10:00.210 --> 00:10:04.330
What's it like to revisit
this show now, in 2018?

00:10:04.330 --> 00:10:05.580
LYNN AHRENS: Oh, it's amazing.

00:10:05.580 --> 00:10:10.380
I mean, none of you, I'm quite
sure, saw the original in 1990.

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:13.890
But this is
completely different,

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:15.150
this incarnation of the show.

00:10:15.150 --> 00:10:17.170
It's almost like night and day.

00:10:17.170 --> 00:10:19.000
It's very contemporary.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:20.400
It's very edgy.

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:23.540
There's real sand,
real fire, real water.

00:10:23.540 --> 00:10:28.260
It is set very groundedly in
Haiti after a big disaster.

00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:31.290
And it sort of relates not
only to Puerto Rico and all

00:10:31.290 --> 00:10:35.040
the disasters in the world
that have ruined and hurt

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:37.950
communities, but has also
brought communities together.

00:10:37.950 --> 00:10:40.230
And the concept
of this production

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:44.130
is that the people who've all
been caught in the storm--

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:48.660
out of disaster comes beauty and
community and music and dance

00:10:48.660 --> 00:10:50.440
and joy and storytelling.

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:54.070
And it has taken the
show to another place

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:56.060
that we never ever expected.

00:10:56.060 --> 00:10:58.460
And to be honest,
at the beginning,

00:10:58.460 --> 00:10:59.680
I could not visualize it.

00:10:59.680 --> 00:11:02.380
I would come home every night
from our technical rehearsals,

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:04.560
and my husband would
say, how's it going?

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:07.770
And I would say, I have no idea.

00:11:07.770 --> 00:11:11.350
I'm sitting in a sandpit,
and it's strewn with garbage,

00:11:11.350 --> 00:11:12.280
and there's a goat.

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:14.080
I don't really know
what's happening.

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:14.890
I couldn't see it.

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:17.200
And then little by little,
I began to really, really

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:19.570
understand and appreciate it.

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:22.330
And it's such a beautiful,
special production.

00:11:22.330 --> 00:11:23.765
And these guys are unbelievable.

00:11:23.765 --> 00:11:24.310
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: It's great.

00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:26.809
In the first row, they actually
have their feet in the sand.

00:11:26.809 --> 00:11:30.970
And the fact that we're doing it
in the round is so revelatory.

00:11:30.970 --> 00:11:33.640
I've only seen it in a
proscenium sort of situation,

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:35.530
so this is great,
because it's really

00:11:35.530 --> 00:11:38.650
about a dialogue between
the audience and the actors.

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:41.380
And this cast, they
are spectacular.

00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:44.770
I mean, each and every one
of them have been handpicked.

00:11:44.770 --> 00:11:47.560
And together, they just are
the most joyous community

00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:49.129
that you'd ever want to hear.

00:11:49.129 --> 00:11:50.420
SPEAKER: Yeah, I mean, I agree.

00:11:50.420 --> 00:11:54.767
And I would love to talk to
you all about your involvement

00:11:54.767 --> 00:11:56.350
with this show before
this production,

00:11:56.350 --> 00:11:58.690
because I know some of
you had done this show.

00:11:58.690 --> 00:12:00.449
Kenita, this is--
what number is this?

00:12:00.449 --> 00:12:02.740
KENITA R. MILLER: I think
this is maybe the sixth time.

00:12:02.740 --> 00:12:03.630
SPEAKER: The sixth time.

00:12:03.630 --> 00:12:04.667
KENITA R. MILLER: Yeah.

00:12:04.667 --> 00:12:06.250
I said, I'm going
to play Tonton next.

00:12:06.250 --> 00:12:09.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:09.630 --> 00:12:11.620
No, but it's awesome.

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:13.840
I mean, it is kind
of a magical show.

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:15.340
Not kind of, it is.

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:16.420
It's very infectious.

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:21.040
And this production is
my absolute favorite

00:12:21.040 --> 00:12:22.510
because of the people.

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:23.470
It's very spoiling.

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:25.678
You don't get to pick who
you work with all the time.

00:12:25.678 --> 00:12:28.540
But we have a
great family, which

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:32.740
makes it really easy to kind of
try to recreate that community.

00:12:32.740 --> 00:12:35.050
And also, just the elements.

00:12:35.050 --> 00:12:39.250
Really, there's a
lot of difficulties

00:12:39.250 --> 00:12:42.280
to working in sand,
but there is so much

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:43.690
beauty in working in it, too.

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:45.940
I mean, I take any
opportunity to roll around

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:47.980
in it when I can.

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:50.260
It's like really
playing on the beach.

00:12:50.260 --> 00:12:55.300
And as an artist, to have these
actual elements to work with,

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:57.820
all you have to do is
show up and be present,

00:12:57.820 --> 00:12:59.807
because it's not much
you have to imagine

00:12:59.807 --> 00:13:00.890
as far as the environment.

00:13:00.890 --> 00:13:02.392
It's right there.

00:13:02.392 --> 00:13:04.600
SPEAKER: I mean, Michael
Arden has a beautiful vision

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:06.490
for this show.

00:13:06.490 --> 00:13:08.650
And there are a lot
of the elements,

00:13:08.650 --> 00:13:10.690
literally, like
earth, wind, and fire.

00:13:10.690 --> 00:13:13.180
You know, hello.

00:13:13.180 --> 00:13:15.190
Is that challenging
for you as actors,

00:13:15.190 --> 00:13:17.980
to sort of navigate
through that and interact

00:13:17.980 --> 00:13:19.940
with those elements, and then--

00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:22.650
KENITA R. MILLER: He's in the
water for the whole evening.

00:13:22.650 --> 00:13:23.887
He's splashing around.

00:13:23.887 --> 00:13:24.970
SPEAKER: Water god, right.

00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:26.220
QUENTIN EARL DARRINGTON: I am.

00:13:26.220 --> 00:13:29.470
I'm in the water
a good 40%, 50%--

00:13:29.470 --> 00:13:31.840
no, maybe more than that.

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:35.290
60%, 70% of the show,
through the entire time.

00:13:35.290 --> 00:13:37.960
So since I had to stay in
the water most of the show,

00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:40.892
I decided to make the most out
of it and the best out of it.

00:13:40.892 --> 00:13:41.850
So I play in the water.

00:13:41.850 --> 00:13:42.600
I throw the water.

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:43.420
I splash the water.

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:45.280
You know, I and
the water are one.

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:48.010
So it's a lot a lot of fun.

00:13:48.010 --> 00:13:50.560
You said challenging.

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:52.210
I mean, it has some challenges.

00:13:52.210 --> 00:13:53.620
It's cold some days.

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:55.540
It's warmer some days.

00:13:55.540 --> 00:13:56.911
But I mean, it's fun.

00:13:56.911 --> 00:13:58.660
You know, at the end
of the day, it's fun.

00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:00.990
So I don't look at it
as a challenge at all.

00:14:00.990 --> 00:14:04.010
I look for every single
day is new opportunities,

00:14:04.010 --> 00:14:05.260
new blessings, new fun.

00:14:05.260 --> 00:14:08.020
So it's fun every single day.

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:11.680
SPEAKER: Loren, we were
talking a little bit backstage.

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:14.144
And you also had an earlier
experience with "Once

00:14:14.144 --> 00:14:14.810
On This Island."

00:14:14.810 --> 00:14:16.730
Tell us about that.

00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:18.586
LOREN LOTT: Yes,
when I was 15, I

00:14:18.586 --> 00:14:19.960
was offered the
role of Ti Moune,

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:21.459
and I turned it
down, because I just

00:14:21.459 --> 00:14:23.470
thought it was way too big.

00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:26.930
So then they had me
do Erzulie instead.

00:14:26.930 --> 00:14:30.312
And I was like a fetus Erzulie
among all of these adults.

00:14:30.312 --> 00:14:32.770
But that was when I completely
fell in love with this show.

00:14:32.770 --> 00:14:33.790
SPEAKER: Oh, wow.

00:14:33.790 --> 00:14:35.720
So this is fascinating,
because it's,

00:14:35.720 --> 00:14:38.920
in a way, a revisiting
and a re-imagining

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:41.630
for you two, but also for
many of the cast members.

00:14:41.630 --> 00:14:42.940
Rodrick, had you had--

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:45.550
did you know about the show?

00:14:45.550 --> 00:14:48.200
RODRICK COVINGTON: No, I didn't
know anything about the show.

00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:50.890
I mean, I know about Stephen
and Lynn and their work,

00:14:50.890 --> 00:14:53.564
but I hadn't seen the show or--

00:14:53.564 --> 00:14:54.730
I mean, I heard of the show.

00:14:54.730 --> 00:14:56.275
But I hadn't seen
it or anything.

00:14:56.275 --> 00:15:01.390
But when we started working
on it, in the reading--

00:15:01.390 --> 00:15:03.270
actually, before the reading.

00:15:03.270 --> 00:15:05.960
It was when I got material and
just started working on it.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:07.480
I just fell in love with it.

00:15:07.480 --> 00:15:09.520
And I was like, oh my
God, if there's anything

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:12.490
that I want to do in the
next season, it is this.

00:15:12.490 --> 00:15:15.410
And I start praying that
I would get the show.

00:15:15.410 --> 00:15:15.910
And--

00:15:15.910 --> 00:15:17.410
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: I think we
all felt that way, you know?

00:15:17.410 --> 00:15:20.050
It just felt like it was
meant to be at this time.

00:15:20.050 --> 00:15:22.330
And there's something
about it being very timely.

00:15:22.330 --> 00:15:26.770
And from the minute we had
our first meeting with Michael

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:28.900
Arden and Ken
Davenport, our producer,

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:31.870
and our two orchestrators
Michael Starobin and AnnMarie

00:15:31.870 --> 00:15:35.920
Milazzo, from that time till--

00:15:35.920 --> 00:15:36.880
we said yes.

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:39.289
And then from the
moment of yes to we're

00:15:39.289 --> 00:15:41.080
in front of an audience,
it was only a year

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:43.900
and a half, which
is really fast,

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:47.005
because we've been pushing
other shows very slowly along.

00:15:47.005 --> 00:15:48.880
But this one, I think
everybody just thought,

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:50.440
this is the time to do this.

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:53.010
And there was an
urgency about it.

00:15:53.010 --> 00:15:56.970
SPEAKER: Yeah, I mean, the
show does feel very current.

00:15:56.970 --> 00:15:59.700
What was that
decision-making process like?

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:02.160
How did they approach
you about it?

00:16:02.160 --> 00:16:03.570
What were the
conversations like?

00:16:03.570 --> 00:16:07.607
And why is now a good
time for this show?

00:16:07.607 --> 00:16:09.440
LYNN AHRENS: Well, right
now is a great time

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:13.550
for theater, period,
because look where we are.

00:16:13.550 --> 00:16:14.407
We need community.

00:16:14.407 --> 00:16:15.740
We need to get in the same room.

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:16.912
We need to have dialogue.

00:16:16.912 --> 00:16:17.870
That's what theater is.

00:16:17.870 --> 00:16:21.380
So you know, our show
feels very topical.

00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:22.820
But I think almost
any show feels

00:16:22.820 --> 00:16:26.900
very topical at the moment.

00:16:26.900 --> 00:16:31.550
Michael Arden is
a genius, I think.

00:16:31.550 --> 00:16:34.430
He was an actor to begin with,
and he's an amazing actor

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:35.870
and an amazing singer.

00:16:35.870 --> 00:16:39.350
And who knew that he had this
directorial genius in him

00:16:39.350 --> 00:16:40.220
as well?

00:16:40.220 --> 00:16:42.417
He did a show on Broadway
a few seasons ago

00:16:42.417 --> 00:16:43.500
called "Spring Awakening."

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:44.557
It was a revival.

00:16:44.557 --> 00:16:46.640
And they did it with the
Deaf West Theatre, right?

00:16:46.640 --> 00:16:48.870
And it was all signed,
and it was beautiful.

00:16:48.870 --> 00:16:51.480
And when he came to
us, first of all,

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:53.720
he wanted to do
this show a capella.

00:16:53.720 --> 00:16:54.860
And we objected to that.

00:16:54.860 --> 00:16:56.725
We said, we need a drum.

00:16:56.725 --> 00:16:58.100
We need some
musical instruments.

00:16:58.100 --> 00:16:58.870
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: I just
thought it was going

00:16:58.870 --> 00:16:59.994
to be like a doo-wop thing.

00:16:59.994 --> 00:17:02.660
I said, is this going to
be like the Pentatonix?

00:17:02.660 --> 00:17:03.864
It felt very odd to me.

00:17:03.864 --> 00:17:05.030
And I said, you need a drum.

00:17:05.030 --> 00:17:06.200
You need this primal drum.

00:17:06.200 --> 00:17:07.190
You need a bass.

00:17:07.190 --> 00:17:09.160
And then we had
more conversations--

00:17:09.160 --> 00:17:10.910
LYNN AHRENS: Yeah, he
brought us drawings.

00:17:10.910 --> 00:17:13.280
He started to bring
drawings and show us

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:18.020
visuals that were not exactly
like what we ended up with,

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:20.000
but they implied Haiti.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.589
They implied children.

00:17:21.589 --> 00:17:25.460
They implied, you know,
certain magical elements

00:17:25.460 --> 00:17:28.430
and fantastical elements and
certain very grim elements

00:17:28.430 --> 00:17:29.400
as well.

00:17:29.400 --> 00:17:30.969
And what we've
realized along the way

00:17:30.969 --> 00:17:32.510
with Michael is--
and we kept saying,

00:17:32.510 --> 00:17:33.810
well, that's interesting.

00:17:33.810 --> 00:17:35.420
Well, why don't you
go away and bring

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:37.610
us the broomstick
of the Wicked Witch,

00:17:37.610 --> 00:17:38.810
and then we'll talk again.

00:17:38.810 --> 00:17:40.143
And then he would bring it back.

00:17:40.143 --> 00:17:41.450
And we would talk again.

00:17:41.450 --> 00:17:43.480
And finally, he won us over.

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:46.970
We thought, this all sounds
good and interesting.

00:17:46.970 --> 00:17:49.130
And the whole point
of doing a revival

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:50.740
is to do something different.

00:17:50.740 --> 00:17:52.631
The show has been
established in one way,

00:17:52.631 --> 00:17:55.130
and why not try to shake it up
and do it in a different way?

00:17:55.130 --> 00:17:58.070
So as the authors, it's a big
risk, because "Once On This

00:17:58.070 --> 00:18:00.380
Island" gets done all over
the country in schools.

00:18:00.380 --> 00:18:03.500
And it's sort of a wonderful,
beloved show, in a way,

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:05.160
for generations of people.

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:08.090
And so to say, OK, you can
bring it back to Broadway,

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:10.040
and we don't quite
understand your concept,

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:12.590
but it sounds really
interesting, was a risk for us.

00:18:12.590 --> 00:18:13.730
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: The
thing that was exciting,

00:18:13.730 --> 00:18:15.560
though, is from the
very first meeting,

00:18:15.560 --> 00:18:18.217
he wanted to be
very ritualistic.

00:18:18.217 --> 00:18:19.550
He wanted to do it in the round.

00:18:19.550 --> 00:18:21.260
He wanted to have the
audience very close

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:24.230
and participating in the story.

00:18:24.230 --> 00:18:27.410
And of course, there's only
one Broadway theater that

00:18:27.410 --> 00:18:30.860
is in the round, and so there
was no Plan B. So it's like,

00:18:30.860 --> 00:18:34.640
either we had to be in Circle
In The Square or not do it.

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:38.660
And I think we just
willed it into being.

00:18:38.660 --> 00:18:39.980
We just really imagined it.

00:18:39.980 --> 00:18:44.930
And we were fortunate
that they wanted our show,

00:18:44.930 --> 00:18:46.850
and we wanted to be there.

00:18:46.850 --> 00:18:50.124
SPEAKER: Yeah, I'm
curious about sort

00:18:50.124 --> 00:18:52.540
of the process of growing up
with this show, like you did,

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:53.039
Kenita.

00:18:53.039 --> 00:18:57.110
We didn't mention this, but
you actually played Ti Moune.

00:18:57.110 --> 00:18:59.090
How has your relationship
with this show--

00:18:59.090 --> 00:19:01.220
I mean, over 6 times,
has it changed?

00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:03.800
Has your understanding of
the characters changed?

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:05.960
KENITA R. MILLER:
Most definitely.

00:19:05.960 --> 00:19:08.180
I always joke, I'm
definitely not waiting

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:09.740
for life to begin anymore.

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:10.936
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:10.936 --> 00:19:13.222
[INAUDIBLE] Ti
Moune with a walker.

00:19:13.222 --> 00:19:15.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:18.800
But I have fallen in
love with Mama Euralie.

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:20.840
I really have.

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:23.750
One, because I have
aspirations to be a mother,

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:27.870
and I think so that
really speaks to my womb.

00:19:27.870 --> 00:19:28.890
And--

00:19:28.890 --> 00:19:31.510
LYNN AHRENS: Keep
saying, don't do it yet.

00:19:31.510 --> 00:19:34.020
Don't do it yet.

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:38.360
KENITA R. MILLER: And also,
two, this character, it

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:39.980
reminds me of my mother.

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:44.090
And my mom actually did some
missionary work in Haiti.

00:19:44.090 --> 00:19:47.750
And she was actually
assigned to orphaned children

00:19:47.750 --> 00:19:52.400
and was kind of a part of
putting a school back together.

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:54.650
And so I went back and looked
at a lot of the pictures

00:19:54.650 --> 00:19:56.300
that she brought
from-- and it's crazy,

00:19:56.300 --> 00:19:59.720
because the uniform that the
little girl wears in the show

00:19:59.720 --> 00:20:02.500
is almost identical
to what these kids had

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:04.010
in the photos with my mom.

00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:07.734
So I mean, this show has always
been really special to me.

00:20:07.734 --> 00:20:09.650
It was one of the first,
because I got started

00:20:09.650 --> 00:20:11.300
in musical theater really late.

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:14.570
It was one of the first
shows that I saw myself in.

00:20:14.570 --> 00:20:16.580
I saw people that
looked like me.

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:26.660
And the music is infectious,
and the story is, I think--

00:20:26.660 --> 00:20:29.390
you know, it has
its own magic to it.

00:20:29.390 --> 00:20:31.220
And then putting
it all together,

00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:33.320
it's something that I
think a lot of people

00:20:33.320 --> 00:20:35.210
hold very dear to them.

00:20:35.210 --> 00:20:38.090
And I don't even know if
you, Lynn and Stephen,

00:20:38.090 --> 00:20:41.300
if you know what you were
starting when you wrote it.

00:20:41.300 --> 00:20:44.150
It really is
something that I think

00:20:44.150 --> 00:20:47.960
a lot of-- even if you
don't like theater per se,

00:20:47.960 --> 00:20:49.970
it's something that just
really captivates you.

00:20:49.970 --> 00:20:53.837
And it has done that to me
since the beginning, yeah.

00:20:53.837 --> 00:20:55.670
SPEAKER: I mean, this
is a real treat for me

00:20:55.670 --> 00:20:58.340
because this is one of my
favorite Broadway scores

00:20:58.340 --> 00:20:59.900
of all time.

00:20:59.900 --> 00:21:02.710
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: I
gave him $5 to say that.

00:21:02.710 --> 00:21:04.040
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:07.120
Every mention is another five.

00:21:07.120 --> 00:21:09.995
My favorite Broadway
score of all time--

00:21:09.995 --> 00:21:12.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:12.470 --> 00:21:17.990
And it was fascinating to hear
while I was preparing for this,

00:21:17.990 --> 00:21:23.510
you had had relationships with
some of these marvelous actors.

00:21:23.510 --> 00:21:26.840
Quentin and Kenita, you had
actually worked together in--

00:21:26.840 --> 00:21:28.160
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: In "Ragtime."

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:29.510
They were Coalhouse and Sarah.

00:21:29.510 --> 00:21:31.757
KENITA R. MILLER: First
show ever out of school.

00:21:31.757 --> 00:21:33.590
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: Was
that your equity card?

00:21:33.590 --> 00:21:34.631
KENITA R. MILLER: It was.

00:21:34.631 --> 00:21:35.631
It definitely was, yeah.

00:21:35.631 --> 00:21:37.047
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
She was amazing.

00:21:37.047 --> 00:21:39.230
We couldn't believe her
the first time we met her.

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:42.260
She's so tiny, and she just
has this enormous voice

00:21:42.260 --> 00:21:44.090
and this enormous soul.

00:21:44.090 --> 00:21:47.867
And she's incapable of
doing anything false.

00:21:47.867 --> 00:21:49.450
LYNN AHRENS: But we
do collect actors.

00:21:49.450 --> 00:21:49.970
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: She can't.

00:21:49.970 --> 00:21:51.380
LYNN AHRENS: We do like actors.

00:21:51.380 --> 00:21:52.190
We do.

00:21:52.190 --> 00:21:53.606
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
You also learned

00:21:53.606 --> 00:21:54.685
to weed out some of them.

00:21:54.685 --> 00:21:57.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:00.170
SPEAKER: Stay tuned for
the after-show, everybody.

00:22:00.170 --> 00:22:03.074
LYNN AHRENS: We'll
tell you later.

00:22:03.074 --> 00:22:05.240
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: But we
absolutely adore this cast.

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:08.441
And many we've worked with
before, some we haven't.

00:22:08.441 --> 00:22:09.440
LYNN AHRENS: Will again.

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:11.315
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: Yeah,
and it's so exciting.

00:22:11.315 --> 00:22:12.980
You know, you collect them.

