None of you had ever
seen her do it, right?

00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:51.151
LYNN AHRENS: No, we
walked in this morning,

00:23:51.151 --> 00:23:52.131
and we said, really?

00:23:52.131 --> 00:23:52.630
OK.

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:55.213
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: We were told
in the elevator coming up here.

00:23:55.213 --> 00:23:58.370
And I'm like, well,
that's going to be fun.

00:23:58.370 --> 00:23:59.960
LYNN AHRENS: It's live theater.

00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:00.810
You never know.

00:24:00.810 --> 00:24:01.500
LOREN LOTT: The struggle.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:02.420
SPEAKER: The struggle.

00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:07.980
So you play a lot of different
roles in the show, Ti Moune,

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:11.315
Asaka, and Andrea.

00:24:11.315 --> 00:24:12.940
RODRICK COVINGTON:
She plays everybody.

00:24:12.940 --> 00:24:13.860
SPEAKER: Yeah, she plays every--

00:24:13.860 --> 00:24:14.390
OK.

00:24:14.390 --> 00:24:15.390
LOREN LOTT: Every woman.

00:24:15.390 --> 00:24:17.170
SPEAKER: Every woman.

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:20.050
What is it like preparing
for those roles?

00:24:20.050 --> 00:24:25.075
I mean, in any given show,
what are you thinking about?

00:24:25.075 --> 00:24:27.970
What are you working on?

00:24:27.970 --> 00:24:33.520
LOREN LOTT: It's kind of hard to
prepare, because a lot of times

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:34.720
it's really last minute.

00:24:34.720 --> 00:24:36.010
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:38.500
LOREN LOTT: If I'm fortunate
enough to know ahead of time,

00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:40.896
each character I feel
like has different needs

00:24:40.896 --> 00:24:42.020
and wants different things.

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:44.470
So I try to spend at
least a little bit of time

00:24:44.470 --> 00:24:46.630
before that remembering
what they want

00:24:46.630 --> 00:24:48.944
and remembering who they
are, because if there's

00:24:48.944 --> 00:24:50.860
times when I'm on as
several different people,

00:24:50.860 --> 00:24:53.900
then I definitely
will get confused.

00:24:53.900 --> 00:24:56.650
But going on for Ti
Moune is probably

00:24:56.650 --> 00:24:58.960
the easiest one to go
on for, because she

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:00.610
has a consistent story.

00:25:00.610 --> 00:25:02.630
And she's in it the entire time.

00:25:02.630 --> 00:25:05.350
And being in the round, you
can just walk into the world.

00:25:05.350 --> 00:25:07.810
And then I'm in
the world, so it's

00:25:07.810 --> 00:25:11.050
easiest to be focused there.

00:25:11.050 --> 00:25:14.230
But usually, I just call my
vocal coach before the shows

00:25:14.230 --> 00:25:18.460
and just run it with her when
I know that I'm on as Ti Moune.

00:25:18.460 --> 00:25:20.824
I've never gone on for Asaka.

00:25:20.824 --> 00:25:22.180
[SIGHS]

00:25:22.180 --> 00:25:24.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:27.250
But I know it's coming.

00:25:27.250 --> 00:25:31.330
And to prepare for
that, I'll probably

00:25:31.330 --> 00:25:37.180
take a really nice
shot of oregano oil,

00:25:37.180 --> 00:25:38.290
get my voice ready.

00:25:40.972 --> 00:25:46.300
But when I prepare for Andrea, I
just look at a lot of my notes.

00:25:46.300 --> 00:25:49.239
And yeah, that's it.

00:25:49.239 --> 00:25:51.530
She's mostly ensemble, and
then she's like a character.

00:25:51.530 --> 00:25:54.130
So then I just
prepare like that.

00:25:54.130 --> 00:25:57.130
But I can't really
prepare like how

00:25:57.130 --> 00:25:59.710
you would for a regular
show, because I'm thrown on.

00:25:59.710 --> 00:26:01.650
So I don't get to--

00:26:01.650 --> 00:26:05.550
I get to focus, but there's
a lot going on when I'm on.

00:26:05.550 --> 00:26:07.300
And there's a lot to
remember, because I'm

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:09.520
working with a lot of
people behind the scenes

00:26:09.520 --> 00:26:11.700
to help me remember certain
things, like my shoes.

00:26:11.700 --> 00:26:14.382
Like, one time I went on, and
they didn't have my shoes.

00:26:14.382 --> 00:26:16.840
So I went out barefoot-- which
is fine, we're in the sand--

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:19.220
but it's happened several times.

00:26:19.220 --> 00:26:21.745
So then we have to be
communicating backstage.

00:26:21.745 --> 00:26:22.990
So there's a lot going on.

00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:24.670
So I'm not exactly
as focused as I'd

00:26:24.670 --> 00:26:26.530
like to be most of the time.

00:26:26.530 --> 00:26:28.797
But I do the job.

00:26:28.797 --> 00:26:30.130
LYNN AHRENS: She's unbelievable.

00:26:30.130 --> 00:26:33.040
She's like a little
rocket scientist

00:26:33.040 --> 00:26:35.360
with all of these charts
and graphs and things.

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:36.880
And she just, she's amazing.

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:37.588
LOREN LOTT: Lynn.

00:26:39.730 --> 00:26:41.384
LYNN AHRENS: Pretty
rocket scientist.

00:26:44.110 --> 00:26:46.120
SPEAKER: How do you
keep these characters

00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:48.040
sort of organized in your head?

00:26:48.040 --> 00:26:51.840
I mean, you're memorizing
lines for all three of them.

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:53.320
Is that hard to keep track of?

00:26:53.320 --> 00:26:55.640
LOREN LOTT: Well, praise
God, when I was little,

00:26:55.640 --> 00:26:57.502
my hobby when I
was doing shows--

00:26:57.502 --> 00:26:58.960
because I started
when I was seven,

00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:00.470
and then my mom pulled me
out because she was like,

00:27:00.470 --> 00:27:02.830
no, I don't want you
to grow up and, like,

00:27:02.830 --> 00:27:04.240
you're not going to be able
use the bathroom by yourself

00:27:04.240 --> 00:27:05.020
because you're
going to be famous.

00:27:05.020 --> 00:27:06.375
And then you're not going to
be able to go to Disneyland

00:27:06.375 --> 00:27:08.200
because people are going to
follow you to the bathroom.

00:27:08.200 --> 00:27:11.020
So I was like, dang, I want
to go to the bathroom myself.

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:13.004
So I didn't do it.

00:27:13.004 --> 00:27:14.420
So I didn't do it
for a long time.

00:27:14.420 --> 00:27:19.130
But when I started
at seven, I really

00:27:19.130 --> 00:27:22.820
enjoyed memorizing plays.

00:27:22.820 --> 00:27:24.660
Like, when I was
in a show, I liked

00:27:24.660 --> 00:27:26.770
to know everybody's lines.

00:27:26.770 --> 00:27:28.570
And I liked to
memorize everything.

00:27:28.570 --> 00:27:33.790
And then it came in handy
because now, doing this show,

00:27:33.790 --> 00:27:37.160
I have memorized everybody's
lines and everybody's

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:37.660
everything.

00:27:37.660 --> 00:27:38.743
But I keep a lot of notes.

00:27:38.743 --> 00:27:40.260
KENITA R. MILLER: Watch out.

00:27:40.260 --> 00:27:40.720
LOREN LOTT: I'm
coming for you, Agwe.

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:42.675
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: She's
coming after you, Rodrick.

00:27:42.675 --> 00:27:43.758
LOREN LOTT: Yeah, Rodrick.

00:27:43.758 --> 00:27:44.920
I'm coming for you.

00:27:44.920 --> 00:27:46.870
And I keep a lot of videos.

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:48.340
Videos are like my Bible.

00:27:48.340 --> 00:27:52.120
I go through my videos
every other night,

00:27:52.120 --> 00:27:54.529
and I just try to
remember who's doing what.

00:27:54.529 --> 00:27:56.320
But a lot of times,
even when I'm on stage,

00:27:56.320 --> 00:28:00.780
I'm watching everybody and
watching everybody who I cover,

00:28:00.780 --> 00:28:03.299
trying not to miss anything
so I can stay up to date.

00:28:03.299 --> 00:28:04.840
Like, if one character
does something

00:28:04.840 --> 00:28:06.550
with another character and
that becomes their thing,

00:28:06.550 --> 00:28:08.799
I try to make sure I know
it so that I can come and do

00:28:08.799 --> 00:28:12.205
their little, like, thing.

00:28:12.205 --> 00:28:14.650
It's always going.

00:28:14.650 --> 00:28:15.532
I'm losing it.

00:28:15.532 --> 00:28:17.551
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:22.420
SPEAKER: You're hiding it well.

00:28:22.420 --> 00:28:25.160
How are you all preparing
for these roles?

00:28:25.160 --> 00:28:27.670
I mean, you're on
stage for 90 minutes.

00:28:27.670 --> 00:28:29.620
You don't really leave, right?

00:28:29.620 --> 00:28:30.190
Do you leave?

00:28:30.190 --> 00:28:34.037
I mean, for the most
part, you're there.

00:28:34.037 --> 00:28:35.620
QUENTIN EARL DARRINGTON:
No, no, we're

00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:37.769
all pretty much all on
stage the whole show.

00:28:37.769 --> 00:28:40.060
We leave maybe for a quick
second, then right back out,

00:28:40.060 --> 00:28:41.290
all the time.

00:28:41.290 --> 00:28:44.230
SPEAKER: I heard Alex talking
about this idea of a snack

00:28:44.230 --> 00:28:44.770
track.

00:28:44.770 --> 00:28:47.050
Can you tell us what
a snack track is?

00:28:47.050 --> 00:28:48.060
And how--

00:28:48.060 --> 00:28:49.643
QUENTIN EARL DARRINGTON:
A snack track

00:28:49.643 --> 00:28:53.140
is a track in a show where
you may have one song,

00:28:53.140 --> 00:28:56.170
and you stay offstage
for most of the show.

00:28:56.170 --> 00:29:00.730
So you come on, you kill
it, and then you leave.

00:29:00.730 --> 00:29:04.690
I used to consider that to be
like Mufasa in "The Lion King."

00:29:04.690 --> 00:29:08.110
Now, I played Mufasa,
and I loved the track.

00:29:08.110 --> 00:29:13.250
You sing one song,
and then you die.

00:29:13.250 --> 00:29:15.680
And then you stay back
the whole second act.

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:17.730
You're in your
dressing room chilling.

00:29:17.730 --> 00:29:19.270
Oh, that's a snack track.

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:21.260
SPEAKER: OK.

00:29:21.260 --> 00:29:23.490
And there are no snack
tracks in this show.

00:29:23.490 --> 00:29:25.259
QUENTIN EARL DARRINGTON: No.

00:29:25.259 --> 00:29:27.367
KENITA R. MILLER: Rodrick
covers Papa Ge, too.

00:29:27.367 --> 00:29:28.200
SPEAKER: Oh, really?

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:28.980
OK, tell me about that.

00:29:28.980 --> 00:29:29.470
LYNN AHRENS: He's amazing.

00:29:29.470 --> 00:29:31.040
LOREN LOTT: It's delicious.

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:34.087
SPEAKER: Oh, I can
see that, yeah.

00:29:34.087 --> 00:29:36.420
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: Can you see
him as the demon of death?

00:29:36.420 --> 00:29:37.770
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:29:37.770 --> 00:29:41.160
SPEAKER: You're so sweet, but I
could just see embodying that.

00:29:41.160 --> 00:29:42.600
What's that process like?

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:45.900
And how are you creating
that character, but also,

00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:48.750
as a storyteller, how are
you-- what's your character

00:29:48.750 --> 00:29:50.130
development like?

00:29:50.130 --> 00:29:54.420
RODRICK COVINGTON: I mean,
when I first auditioned,

00:29:54.420 --> 00:29:56.040
everything was for Papa Ge.

00:29:56.040 --> 00:30:00.330
So everything that I was doing
in preparation was for Papa Ge.

00:30:00.330 --> 00:30:05.640
And so just going in it, I
just saw myself as Papa Ge.

00:30:05.640 --> 00:30:10.950
And I had to adjust more and to
get more into as a storyteller.

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:16.320
And the storyteller is actually
much more work than Papa Ge,

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:21.540
because the storyteller is
constantly on stage and moving

00:30:21.540 --> 00:30:25.240
and changing and doing so much.

00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:29.500
As Papa Ge, there's
just this one linear--

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:36.150
and I really feel like I was
already prepared for that,

00:30:36.150 --> 00:30:38.850
in just the root of it, of
even where Papa Ge comes from,

00:30:38.850 --> 00:30:41.760
even just from the voodoo.

00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:47.877
And so doing that just honestly
just feels completely right.

00:30:47.877 --> 00:30:49.710
You know, I don't ever
get to do that often.

00:30:49.710 --> 00:30:51.699
But when I do.

00:30:51.699 --> 00:30:52.990
KENITA R. MILLER: It's amazing.

00:30:52.990 --> 00:30:53.540
LOREN LOTT: We love it.

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:54.480
KENITA R. MILLER: We
have a woman that plays--

00:30:54.480 --> 00:30:56.420
RODRICK COVINGTON: Yeah,
and she's incredible.

00:30:56.420 --> 00:30:57.836
LYNN AHRENS: Yeah,
we have a woman

00:30:57.836 --> 00:31:00.510
playing the god of death, which
is traditionally a man's role.

00:31:00.510 --> 00:31:03.077
And we have a man playing
Asaka, mother of the Earth,

00:31:03.077 --> 00:31:04.660
which is traditionally
a woman's role.

00:31:04.660 --> 00:31:06.650
So we've shaken up the
genders a little bit

00:31:06.650 --> 00:31:08.280
in this production,
which also makes

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:11.970
it really contemporary in
a way and feel unusual.

