00:32:29.340 --> 00:32:30.630
Take a question over here.

00:32:30.630 --> 00:32:31.370
AUDIENCE: Hi, everyone.

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:32.580
Thank you so much
for being here.

00:32:32.580 --> 00:32:33.621
I've seen the show twice.

00:32:33.621 --> 00:32:34.274
I love it.

00:32:34.274 --> 00:32:35.940
I have a question
about the instruments,

00:32:35.940 --> 00:32:38.160
because there's a lot of
interesting instruments.

00:32:38.160 --> 00:32:42.470
And I'm curious how those have
changed for this production

00:32:42.470 --> 00:32:43.567
than before.

00:32:43.567 --> 00:32:45.150
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
Yeah, originally, we

00:32:45.150 --> 00:32:47.374
had a little band
of five people.

00:32:47.374 --> 00:32:49.040
So they're like a
little Caribbean band.

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:52.470
But off Michael Arden's
idea of, what if everything

00:32:52.470 --> 00:32:53.370
was taken from you?

00:32:53.370 --> 00:32:54.630
How would you create music?

00:32:54.630 --> 00:32:57.570
How would you tell your story?

00:32:57.570 --> 00:33:00.960
We came upon the notion
of actually inventing

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:03.000
some instruments that
are made out of discards,

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.139
out of trash, out
of found objects.

00:33:05.139 --> 00:33:06.680
And our orchestrator
Michael Starobin

00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:08.910
has a good friend named
John Bertles, who has

00:33:08.910 --> 00:33:11.014
a group called Bash The Trash.

00:33:11.014 --> 00:33:12.430
And that's literally
what they do.

00:33:12.430 --> 00:33:14.760
They make instruments
out of trash.

00:33:14.760 --> 00:33:17.550
And there's something about
making music or repurposing

00:33:17.550 --> 00:33:21.120
something to create a thing
of beauty which we were really

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:21.900
excited about.

00:33:21.900 --> 00:33:25.357
So they play all sorts of little
strange and interesting things

00:33:25.357 --> 00:33:26.190
throughout the show.

00:33:26.190 --> 00:33:28.523
LYNN AHRENS: They whirl tubes
that are actually pitched,

00:33:28.523 --> 00:33:31.790
so it's like E-flat,
or whatever it is.

00:33:31.790 --> 00:33:34.290
And we have a little girl in
the show-- two little girls,

00:33:34.290 --> 00:33:35.940
actually, and they're
both musicians,

00:33:35.940 --> 00:33:37.530
very, very talented musicians.

00:33:37.530 --> 00:33:40.110
And I love when one of
them is in the show.

00:33:40.110 --> 00:33:41.061
And she's a cellist.

00:33:41.061 --> 00:33:43.560
And she plays a little cello,
but it's made out of, I think,

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:46.927
a cardboard box and some
strings and wires and stuff.

00:33:46.927 --> 00:33:49.260
And it's just adorable, you
know, and it actually plays.

00:33:49.260 --> 00:33:51.480
So it's all that.

00:33:51.480 --> 00:33:54.220
Glass Coke bottles and
all sorts of good stuff.

00:33:54.220 --> 00:33:55.636
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
So we still have

00:33:55.636 --> 00:33:58.740
our little combo,
little island band,

00:33:58.740 --> 00:34:00.450
but with the trash instruments.

00:34:00.450 --> 00:34:03.900
And also, we were experimenting
with the idea of, instead

00:34:03.900 --> 00:34:06.570
of using synth pads
like we did originally,

00:34:06.570 --> 00:34:08.879
creating those textures
with the human voice.

00:34:08.879 --> 00:34:09.760
LYNN AHRENS: Voices.

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:13.734
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: And so we have
a beautiful vocal arrangement

00:34:13.734 --> 00:34:15.900
that functions as part of
the orchestration, created

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:18.810
by AnnMarie Milazzo, who did
all the vocal work on "Spring

00:34:18.810 --> 00:34:19.860
Awakening."

00:34:19.860 --> 00:34:22.550
And she's wildly inventive.

00:34:22.550 --> 00:34:25.030
And they're amazing that
they can execute this stuff,

00:34:25.030 --> 00:34:25.350
because it's tricky.

00:34:25.350 --> 00:34:26.830
LYNN AHRENS: And all that's
new in this production.

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:28.429
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
It's all new, yeah.

00:34:28.429 --> 00:34:28.820
AUDIENCE: Wonderful.

00:34:28.820 --> 00:34:29.319
Thank you.

00:34:31.761 --> 00:34:33.469
SPEAKER: What's it
like to hear the music

00:34:33.469 --> 00:34:35.959
with those sort of found
objects and instruments?

00:34:35.959 --> 00:34:38.000
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: Well,
you know, the whole thing

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:40.340
was a big process
of experimentation.

00:34:40.340 --> 00:34:44.799
I think there's something about
going into a revival where you

00:34:44.799 --> 00:34:48.230
know that the show itself works,
so it actually frees you up

00:34:48.230 --> 00:34:51.389
to try a lot more other things.

00:34:51.389 --> 00:34:52.639
And this is one of the things.

00:34:52.639 --> 00:34:55.460
And it was sort of like a-- we
had a series of small workshops

00:34:55.460 --> 00:34:57.740
where we had experiment
with these vocals

00:34:57.740 --> 00:35:00.290
and then these ideas
for the instruments.

00:35:00.290 --> 00:35:05.360
And using the voice, it actually
makes the show more human,

00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:09.722
because actually, it's
different voices supporting

00:35:09.722 --> 00:35:10.430
the other voices.

00:35:10.430 --> 00:35:13.880
And there's something about
that that just grabs you.

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:16.850
SPEAKER: Great Let's take
a question over here.

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:19.010
AUDIENCE: I've loved this
score for a long time,

00:35:19.010 --> 00:35:20.910
listened to the
soundtrack many times

00:35:20.910 --> 00:35:22.790
and waited many
years for a revival.

00:35:22.790 --> 00:35:24.350
And this one was amazing.

00:35:24.350 --> 00:35:29.420
But I always thought that maybe
it wasn't revived on Broadway

00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:30.410
because it's short.

00:35:30.410 --> 00:35:32.300
It's a one-act.

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:33.380
Was I right about that?

00:35:33.380 --> 00:35:35.987
And if I was, did you ever
consider making it longer?

00:35:35.987 --> 00:35:38.070
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: I don't
think it was the length.

00:35:38.070 --> 00:35:38.876
LYNN AHRENS: I don't think
it was the length either.

00:35:38.876 --> 00:35:39.090
Go ahead.

00:35:39.090 --> 00:35:40.910
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: It
seems like these days,

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:42.590
theater pieces want
to get shorter,

00:35:42.590 --> 00:35:44.940
and movies are just
getting longer, you know?

00:35:44.940 --> 00:35:46.670
I mean, movies are so long now.

00:35:46.670 --> 00:35:48.890
But I don't think that
that was ever an issue.

00:35:48.890 --> 00:35:52.560
I know when we took it to
London, the London people,

00:35:52.560 --> 00:35:53.960
they like that full night out.

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:55.340
And they said, can't we create--

00:35:55.340 --> 00:35:56.090
LYNN AHRENS: Can't
we go to the bar?

00:35:56.090 --> 00:35:57.190
STEPHEN FLAHERTY:
Can't we go to the bar?

00:35:57.190 --> 00:35:59.023
Can't we create-- and
we said, no, it really

00:35:59.023 --> 00:35:59.990
doesn't want a break.

00:35:59.990 --> 00:36:03.020
So what they did is they
ripped apart the theater,

00:36:03.020 --> 00:36:05.360
and they made it into
a Caribbean village.

00:36:05.360 --> 00:36:07.340
And they had all
sorts of Caribbean--

00:36:07.340 --> 00:36:08.360
LYNN AHRENS: Goat pies.

00:36:08.360 --> 00:36:10.010
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: --goat
pies and Caribbean bands

00:36:10.010 --> 00:36:10.550
playing after.

00:36:10.550 --> 00:36:12.424
So they had like an
after-show kind of thing.

00:36:12.424 --> 00:36:14.400
So it was like you could
just hang and do that.

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:16.316
LYNN AHRENS: I think
it's just taken this long

00:36:16.316 --> 00:36:19.340
because it's just taken
this long, you know?

00:36:19.340 --> 00:36:21.830
I don't think there's any
real reason other than it just

00:36:21.830 --> 00:36:24.020
takes somebody to fall
in love with something

00:36:24.020 --> 00:36:26.810
and have a vision for it and
say, I want to bring this back.

00:36:28.899 --> 00:36:31.190
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: There was
always talk about revivals,

00:36:31.190 --> 00:36:34.090
but I'm glad it didn't happen
until now, because I think

00:36:34.090 --> 00:36:36.380
we needed to wait for
the right group of people

00:36:36.380 --> 00:36:40.405
to manifest themselves and
sort of show up in time.

00:36:40.405 --> 00:36:41.030
AUDIENCE: Great

00:36:41.030 --> 00:36:41.988
LYNN AHRENS: Thank you.

00:36:45.260 --> 00:36:47.420
AUDIENCE: Thank you so
much for coming to Google.

00:36:47.420 --> 00:36:48.890
This question is
mainly for Lynn,

00:36:48.890 --> 00:36:51.410
because I was really
struck by how you mentioned

00:36:51.410 --> 00:36:55.080
the importance of community and
the arts bringing us together.

00:36:55.080 --> 00:36:57.740
I work on YouTube, so I'm always
very curious and excited when

00:36:57.740 --> 00:36:58.790
creators come in.

00:36:58.790 --> 00:37:01.850
How do you think that
YouTube specifically, maybe

00:37:01.850 --> 00:37:03.410
Google in general,
could do a better

00:37:03.410 --> 00:37:07.250
job of supporting the arts and
engaging those conversations

00:37:07.250 --> 00:37:10.196
through our online platforms?

00:37:10.196 --> 00:37:11.100
LYNN AHRENS: Uh-oh.

00:37:11.100 --> 00:37:11.771
Well--

00:37:11.771 --> 00:37:14.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:14.660 --> 00:37:18.161
I think you do a great
job to begin with.

00:37:18.161 --> 00:37:21.359
Years ago, I wrote
songs and sang

00:37:21.359 --> 00:37:23.900
for a show called "Schoolhouse
Rock," which maybe some of you

00:37:23.900 --> 00:37:24.920
grew up with.

00:37:24.920 --> 00:37:26.990
And they're all on YouTube.

00:37:26.990 --> 00:37:29.717
And so I can see my life
flashing before my eyes

00:37:29.717 --> 00:37:30.550
sometimes, you know?

00:37:30.550 --> 00:37:36.230
And it's extraordinary to me
how you can find so many things

00:37:36.230 --> 00:37:38.150
on there and through Google.

00:37:38.150 --> 00:37:41.820
I mean, almost the knowledge
of the world at our fingertips.

00:37:41.820 --> 00:37:43.760
And I love that.

00:37:43.760 --> 00:37:45.750
I don't know how you
could do a better job.

00:37:45.750 --> 00:37:47.540
But maybe-- is there
a theater channel

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:49.850
in your future or something?

00:37:49.850 --> 00:37:53.360
You know, live performance
is very ephemeral.

00:37:53.360 --> 00:37:56.960
You see it one night, and
Alex Newell is playing Asaka.

00:37:56.960 --> 00:37:59.720
You see it the next
night, and Loren Lott

00:37:59.720 --> 00:38:02.780
is playing Asaka because
Alex got ill or whatever.

00:38:02.780 --> 00:38:04.364
You know, one night
an actor is on,

00:38:04.364 --> 00:38:05.780
the next night
they're not as good

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:08.030
because they're not feeling
as well or whatever it is.

00:38:08.030 --> 00:38:12.750
So to capture live theater,
I think, is very important.

00:38:12.750 --> 00:38:15.530
And the more we can do
that, within legal limits,

00:38:15.530 --> 00:38:16.910
the better.

00:38:16.910 --> 00:38:18.320
There's a lot of
stuff on YouTube

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:21.510
that people sort of hold the
camera up and then stick it

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:22.760
under their coat or something.

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:24.410
And we don't want that so much.

00:38:24.410 --> 00:38:26.670
But maybe there's
something in that idea.

00:38:26.670 --> 00:38:29.400
I don't know how you
would do your job better.

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:31.400
I feel I'm in the heart
of technology right now.

00:38:31.400 --> 00:38:33.470
It's like the
belly of the beast.

00:38:33.470 --> 00:38:34.700
It's really cool.

00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:35.414
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:35.414 --> 00:38:37.580
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: There's
something really exciting,

00:38:37.580 --> 00:38:40.140
though, about the idea
of global community,

00:38:40.140 --> 00:38:43.010
because that really didn't
exist before the advent

00:38:43.010 --> 00:38:44.900
of the internet and all of that.

00:38:44.900 --> 00:38:45.380
LYNN AHRENS: That's right.

00:38:45.380 --> 00:38:46.970
STEPHEN FLAHERTY: I find that
that's potentially really

00:38:46.970 --> 00:38:48.880
exciting, just the idea
of that interfacing.

00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:49.975
LYNN AHRENS: Yes, exactly.

00:38:49.975 --> 00:38:50.600
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:51.180
Thank you so much.

00:38:51.180 --> 00:38:51.660
LYNN AHRENS: Thank you.

00:38:51.660 --> 00:38:52.734
Thanks for asking that.

00:38:52.734 --> 00:38:54.650
SPEAKER: Quentin, we
were talking a little bit

00:38:54.650 --> 00:39:00.650
about craft and sort
of learning your craft

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:03.290
and honing your craft.

00:39:03.290 --> 00:39:07.640
What's your perspective on the
whole sort of digital landscape

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:11.090
as it relates to young
artists coming up?

00:39:11.090 --> 00:39:14.360
Obviously, a lot of people
getting discovered on YouTube.

00:39:14.360 --> 00:39:16.170
What's your
relationship with that?

00:39:16.170 --> 00:39:16.950
What's your perspective on it?

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:17.420
QUENTIN EARL DARRINGTON:
It's interesting,

00:39:17.420 --> 00:39:19.400
because in this age
of social media,

00:39:19.400 --> 00:39:22.790
things are so, so, so, so fast.

00:39:22.790 --> 00:39:24.110
Information moves so fast.

00:39:24.110 --> 00:39:28.400
We learn so fast, which,
honestly, at a lot of times

00:39:28.400 --> 00:39:31.730
makes audience members'
attention spans shorter.

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:34.670
And just like we said with shows
getting shorter and shorter

00:39:34.670 --> 00:39:37.490
and shorter, these quick
blurbs, these quick things.

00:39:37.490 --> 00:39:39.590
Not too many people
are taking the time

00:39:39.590 --> 00:39:42.080
to read as much anymore
or to take the time

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:45.860
to really sit through a three
and 1/2 hour production.

00:39:45.860 --> 00:39:47.770
I hear "Angels in
America" is back.

00:39:47.770 --> 00:39:51.410
And it's an event,
which I can't wait

00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:54.870
to see and to be a part of.

00:39:54.870 --> 00:39:57.350
I think there's
some pros and cons

00:39:57.350 --> 00:39:59.330
to the way this
push has happened

00:39:59.330 --> 00:40:00.567
for us all moving forward.

00:40:00.567 --> 00:40:02.150
But I hope that
there's a happy medium

00:40:02.150 --> 00:40:04.910
that we can continue to find,
artistically, creatively,

00:40:04.910 --> 00:40:08.870
and for our human nature and
growth all across the board,

00:40:08.870 --> 00:40:12.650
to keep growing and producing
great art and great people.

00:40:12.650 --> 00:40:15.927
SPEAKER: Yeah, Loren, you
were on "American Idol."

00:40:15.927 --> 00:40:17.510
You've done a lot
of film and TV work,

00:40:17.510 --> 00:40:21.050
but we're talking a
lot about live theater.

00:40:21.050 --> 00:40:24.380
What's it like being
back in the theater?

00:40:24.380 --> 00:40:26.830
Do you prefer one
over the other?

00:40:26.830 --> 00:40:29.354
What are the differences?

00:40:29.354 --> 00:40:31.520
LOREN LOTT: I go back and
forth, because sometimes I

00:40:31.520 --> 00:40:32.900
prefer theater.

00:40:32.900 --> 00:40:35.572
But I prefer theater when
I'm working on TV and film.

00:40:35.572 --> 00:40:37.280
And then when I'm
working on TV and film,

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:40.370
I feel like I
prefer TV and film,

00:40:40.370 --> 00:40:43.010
because there is something
really nice about doing

00:40:43.010 --> 00:40:45.410
one scene, and then
if I mess it up,

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:47.150
just doing it over
and over again,

00:40:47.150 --> 00:40:50.210
and then going back to
my trailer and napping.

00:40:50.210 --> 00:40:53.530
And then crafties, which,
when you're on a set,

00:40:53.530 --> 00:40:55.730
there's food everywhere.

00:40:55.730 --> 00:40:57.440
And it's called crafties.

00:40:57.440 --> 00:40:59.320
And they become
your best friends.

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:01.402
Or they become my best friends.

00:41:01.402 --> 00:41:02.690
But I love that.

00:41:02.690 --> 00:41:04.140
I love crafties.

00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:05.840
Because in theater,
I remember during

00:41:05.840 --> 00:41:08.380
our first few rehearsals, I
hadn't done theater in a while.

00:41:08.380 --> 00:41:09.880
And I was like, so
where's crafties?

00:41:09.880 --> 00:41:12.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:16.370
And Alex Newell laughed at me.

00:41:16.370 --> 00:41:19.110
And then we became friends.

00:41:19.110 --> 00:41:25.604
But I think right now, theater
like this, in our worlds--

00:41:25.604 --> 00:41:27.020
because I feel
like we're actually

00:41:27.020 --> 00:41:29.870
in our own little world, and
it's really, really special.

00:41:29.870 --> 00:41:32.610
And it's really different than
any other show that I've done.

00:41:32.610 --> 00:41:37.080
So right now I prefer the
round, prefer theater.

00:41:37.080 --> 00:41:40.310
SPEAKER: Yeah, one of the last
songs in the show, or actually

00:41:40.310 --> 00:41:42.930
the last song, is "Why
We Tell the Story."

00:41:42.930 --> 00:41:46.960
Can you talk a little bit about
why you all tell the story

00:41:46.960 --> 00:41:48.670
and what the show means to you?

00:41:53.060 --> 00:41:55.660
RODRICK COVINGTON: Well, I
have 18 brothers and sisters

00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:56.630
in Florida.

00:41:56.630 --> 00:41:57.970
My parents had 19 kids.

00:41:57.970 --> 00:42:01.510
And I have over 150
nieces and nephews

00:42:01.510 --> 00:42:04.210
because all of my siblings
have kids except my brother

00:42:04.210 --> 00:42:05.940
and I, who are
the 18th and 17th.

00:42:05.940 --> 00:42:07.940
And then their kids have
kids and kids and kids.

00:42:07.940 --> 00:42:13.300
And so it really is a village,
and like our community

00:42:13.300 --> 00:42:14.120
and tribe.

00:42:14.120 --> 00:42:17.410
And so every time that
we get to that part,

00:42:17.410 --> 00:42:22.120
and the little girl
reminds us of the story,

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:23.710
my heart wells up
every time because I

00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:26.380
think of my nieces
and my nephew,

00:42:26.380 --> 00:42:35.185
particularly Tyra and Tory,
and just how my life right now

00:42:35.185 --> 00:42:37.180
has to be about them.

00:42:37.180 --> 00:42:38.230
You know what I mean?

00:42:38.230 --> 00:42:44.697
And no longer about me, because
it's about the next generation.

00:42:44.697 --> 00:42:46.030
And that's why I tell the story.

00:42:46.030 --> 00:42:50.560
And that's why I'm
so grateful that I

00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:52.180
feel an alignment
of being a part

00:42:52.180 --> 00:42:54.550
of this particular
production, because it's

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:56.480
about the next generation.

00:43:01.235 --> 00:43:03.690
KENITA R. MILLER:
I tell the story

00:43:03.690 --> 00:43:09.720
because I have to, and for
similar reasons, but also

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:13.020
to not to forget.

00:43:13.020 --> 00:43:16.590
We say, hope is why,
faith is why, love is

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:19.210
why, grief is why, pain is why.

00:43:19.210 --> 00:43:22.200
And I think that they
are all emotions that

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:25.010
make us so beautifully human.

00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:27.450
